Bleaching investigation for Platy paper

Kristina Tietjen

02 March, 2020

  1. create a new .Rmd / .html file (in the appropriate Platy Git repo) borrowing code from the tagged coral analysis weve been doing for KI Bleaching MS, and calculate the % of each of the 4 species that were bleached (and ideally also do a table for this in which we know which bleaching category they were i.e.how bleached) in July 2015 and in March/April 2016

  2. from Kims Nov.2015 data, create a spreadsheet (that we can then read into R and do calculations on) with data recorded for the Site, Coral Species, total number of individual colonies of that species that were visible in all photos at that site, total number of individual colonies of that species that were bleached. Then in R, calculate the proportion bleached: overall sites, and by disturbance level.

  3. we should do the same for the SPQ data for July 2015 and March/April 2016 - will sort out these numbers with Jenn and Jessie as theyve been the people primarily working with these data.

  4. compare the coral net version of proportion bleached from novebmer 2015 against the colony level proportion bleached that I tallied from the photos

From i) and ii) I would like to then make a figure that shows the proportion bleached for each of the 4 species at these three time points. -> bar plot

Statistics: We could then do a series of simply models to quantify the following things:

  1. What proportion of tagged coral colonies was bleached in 2015, and did this differ by species (ie. the 4 species) or disturbance level. Suggested model: mixed effects logistic regression with bleached/not-bleached as response, species and disturbance level as fixed effects, site as random effect.

  2. same question but for Nov.2015

  3. What proportion of tagged coral colonies survived (i.e.March/April 2016 timepoint) and was survival higher at lower levels of disturbance (and did survival differ by species). Same type of model

ii)

Platy
In the photos from Kim Cobb from November 2015 there were s 108 Platygyra. There were 92 that were not showing any signs of bleaching. That is 85.1851852% of the Platys. Only 9 had level 1 bleaching, 4 had level 2, and 2 had level 3.

There were 19 at medium disturbance sites - 11 of them were healthy (57.8947368%). Only 2 were full bleached (level 3). There were 88 at VH sites - 80 were not bleached and there were none that were fully bleached. There was only 1 platy at VL sites but it was not bleached. There were not many photos from BOW though.

Hydno
In the photos from Kim Cobb from November 2015 there were s 175 Hydnophora. There were 45 that were not showing any signs of bleaching. That is 25.7142857% of the hydnos. Only 2 had level 1 bleaching, 8 had level 2, but 117 had level 3.

There were 18 at medium disturbance sites - 15 of them were healthy (83.3333333%), 1 were full bleached (level 3) (5.5555556%). There were 155 at VH sites - 1 were not bleached and there were 114 fully bleached. There was only 2 at VL sites but they were all fully bleached. There were not many photos from BOW though.

F. pentagona
In the photos from Kim Cobb from November 2015 there were s 175 F. pentagona. There were 8 that were not showing any signs of bleaching. That is 4.5714286% of the F. pentagona. Only 8 had level 1 bleaching, 4 had level 2, but 11 had level 3.

There were 4 at medium disturbance sites - 1 of them were healthy (25%), 5 were full bleached (level 3) (125%). There were 31 at VH sites - 11 were not bleached and there were none fully bleached. There was only 1 at VL sites and it was a level 2 bleaching. There were not many photos from BOW though.

Favia spp
In the photos from Kim Cobb from November 2015 there were s 232 Favia spp. There were 15 that were not showing any signs of bleaching. That is 6.4655172% of the F. pentagona. Only 27 had level 1 bleaching, 8 had level 2, but 180 had level 3.

There were 14 at medium disturbance sites - 4 of them were healthy (28.5714286%), 11 were full bleached (level 3) (78.5714286%). There were 217 at VH sites - 8 were not bleached and there 2 fully bleached. There was only 1 at VL sites and it was a level 3 bleaching. There were not many photos from BOW though.

Favia spp
In the photos from Kim Cobb from November 2015 there were s 180 Favid. There were corals that I could tell were a favid but I was unable to tell if it was Favia or Favites. There were 7 that were not showing any signs of bleaching. That is 3.8888889% of the F. pentagona. Only 11 had level 1 bleaching, 16 had level 2, but 136 had level 3.

There were 7 at medium disturbance sites - 2 of them were healthy (28.5714286%), 1 were full bleached (level 3) (14.2857143%). There were 180 at VH sites - 13 were not bleached and there 7 fully bleached. There was none at the VL sites. There were not many photos from BOW though.
